      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: clean up Kiro CLI helper processes",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- launch Kiro CLI commands with a dedicated process group established before `exec`\n- terminate residual helpers after normal parent exit, escalating from `TERM` to `KILL` before draining inherited pipes\n- discover escaped helpers by the exact stdout/stderr pipes they retain\n- cache start-time-verified descendants and same-group members while the root process identity is still valid\n- capture normal-exit process-group members before reaping the root, including helpers spawned by a `SIGTERM` handler\n- signal only processes whose start-time identity still matches, avoiding PID or process-group reuse hazards\n- preserve child standard streams when the host starts with a standard descriptor closed\n- preserve existing timeout, cancellation, output, and exit-status behavior\n\nFollow-up to https://github.com/steipete/CodexBar/issues/1533 and https://github.com/steipete/CodexBar/issues/1535.\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe original Kiro runner could wait indefinitely after termination or parent exit: `waitUntilExit()` had no `KILL` escalation, and final EOF reads remained blocked while descendants retained inherited output pipes.\n\nThe bounded repair establishes a process group before `exec`, records exact output-pipe holders, and snapshots stable process identities before the root is reaped. The exit waiter uses portable blocking `waitid(WEXITED | WNOWAIT)` so same-group helpers can be captured while the unreaped root still prevents PID/PGID reuse. Termination refreshes the identity cache before escalation, covering helpers created during `SIGTERM`. Later signals are sent only to start-time-verified identities; no numeric process-group signal is sent after root exit.\n\n## Proof\n\nExact head: `320d89608dec997d864dec8d3cfa7cf3df004fd1`\n\n- focused Kiro/process tests: 41 passed, including Kiro integration, normal-exit same-group non-pipe helpers, inherited-pipe, escaped-session, reparented same-group, `SIGTERM`-spawned helper, grace-period, ignored-`TERM`, cancellation, and closed-standard-descriptor cases\n- `make test`: 470 deterministic selections across 40 shards passed\n- `make check`: parser/package/release guards passed; SwiftFormat clean; SwiftLint 0 violations across 1117 files\n- `git diff --check`: passed\n- exact local autoreview of the Linux portability repair: clean; no accepted or actionable findings\n- prior release CLI synthetic proofs confirmed normal same-group, escaped-pipe, and idle-termination cleanup without live credentials, browser data, or Keychain access\n\n## Risk\n\nThe new process launcher is package-internal and currently used only by Kiro. Pipe-holder discovery runs only for residual groups or failed EOF drain. Darwin uses `proc_listpids` for process-group enumeration; Linux filters `/proc`. Every terminating signal is gated by a stable process start identity, and normal successful exit cannot target unrelated members of a reused numeric process group.\n",
